"ogimage":"http://s3-media4.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/sMJ8Rmq6Kl4LC19b1eUwLw/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Having lived in the West Kensington/Barons Court area for the last 18 months, it&#39;s kind of telling that I have very few regular eating haunts here.  Either I&#39;ll head eastwrds or I&#39;ll order in from Holy Cow.  Nevertheless, it still has a handful of quality establishments, one of which is Taiwan Village.  Located at the intersection of North End Road and Lillie Road (close to West Brompton Tube, and accessible on the 74/190/430 and 28/391 buses), Taiwan Village sits unassumingly, just opposite the restaurant which used to specialise in Indian and Chinese cuisine (yep, headscratcher that one).<br><br>The interior is small but very nicely furnished, and it&#39;s great for a slightly more intimate meal.  On top of this, the staff (mostly from Burma) are all extra friendly and helpful.  The menu is a mix of Taiwanese, Hunan, and Szechuan cuisine (the chef is Taiwanese), so it&#39;s a bit different from your usual HK-style fare, and also features a lot of chilli.  One thing I do like about this place is that you can ask them to cook a mystery meal for you for a fixed price (can&#39;t remember how much exactly, but it&#39;s maybe a bit less than £25?) which will invariably offer several things that you wouldn&#39;t usually order.<br><br>As far as individual dishes go, I really like the hot and sour soup - I&#39;m on an eternal quest to find the perfect one, and this one is as good as any I&#39;ve tried in London.  They also do some awesome ribs in a fruity, vinegary, spicy sauce.  The French beans fried in a chew yim-esque way are great too.<br><br>Ultimately, this is definitely one of my favourite Chinese restaurants in London.  Whilst the menu may not be as extensive as places such as Bar Shu, it&#39;s much more affordable, and the setting is much more intimate than pretty much any other I can think of - so if you want a quiet couples dinner, this is perfect.  I have been the only customer here at times and I&#39;m a little afraid it might move (although it&#39;s been around for quite a while), given its less-than-obvious location, so I implore you to go and eat!",
